Calling what is given to analyze "sentences" is most cases is fairly generous, or even incorrect, as often there is no discernible subject, action, or object.  What is given are verbal statements, often grammatically incorrect, of which the respondent is asked to differentiate and rate often subtle change in meaning with the inserted phrase, "but not all" after the word "some".  Hence, an interesting, but very subjective  task.  By the way, as long as you asked, the payment offered is more than fair.  Good luck with your research!

Not having the original statements be grammatically correct affects how the secondary statements sound to the ear, regardless of whether the meaning of the statement is changed or not.  Choosing to include verbatim phone transcription instead of correct sentences just makes the task at hand, discerning whether the meaning of the statement is changed by insertion of the phrase "but not all", more difficult- unnecessarily in my opinion.  In any case, best of luck with your project!
